block content

  +state('Connecticut', '/assets/images/flag-connecticut.svg', 'The Constitution State', 'January 9, 1788')

  .intro
    p More than 100 years after statehood, Governor O. William Coffin established a committee to standardize a state flag.
    p An unofficial design had been used prior, inspired by a memorial by the Anna Warner Bailey Chapter of the Daughters of the American Revolution and featuring the Connecticut coat of arms.
    p The flag was officially adopted September 9, 1897.

  .guide
    .content
      h2 Flag design
      p The flag features a field of azure silk on which the state coat of arms is featured in argent white silk. Below the shield is a white streamer, cleft at each end with the Latin words “Qui Transtulit Sustinet” inscribed.
    .visual.flag
      img(src='/assets/images/flag-connecticut.svg')

  .guide.wide
    .content
      h2 Iconography
      ul.visual.icon-list
        li.icon-item
          span.icon: img(src='/assets/images/flag-connecticut-icon-grapevine.svg')
          h4 Grapevine
          p As grapevines are easily transplanted, they represent the pilgrims who settled in Connecticut.
        li.icon-item
          span.icon: img(src='/assets/images/flag-connecticut-icon-three-grapevines.svg')
          h4 3 grapevines
          p The three grapevines together may also symbolize Connecticut’s three oldest settlements of Windsor, Wethersfield, and Hartford.
        li.icon-item
          span.icon: img(src='/assets/images/flag-connecticut-icon-motto.svg')
          h4 Motto
          p “Qui Transtulit Sustinet” translates to “He Who Transplanted Still Sustains” and has been the state motto since 1662.
        li.icon-item

  .guide
    .content
      h2 Coat of Arms
      p While featured on the flag long before, the state coat of arms wasn’t officially adopted until 1931. It was based on the seal for Saybrook Colony, which featured 15 grapevines and the motto “Sustinet qui transtulit.”
    .visual.flag
      img(src='/assets/images/coat-of-arms-connecticut.jpg')

  .guide
    .content
      h2 Colors
      p The flag features a field of azure, accented with white, silver, gold, and other “neutral colors.”
    .visual
      .colors.primary
        .color
          .sample(class='azure')
          .name Azure
          .hex #0c2d83
        include includes/color-white
        .color
          .sample(class='gold')
          .name Gold
          .hex #ffd312
        .color
          .sample(class='silver')
          .name Silver
          .hex #c4c4c4
      .colors.secondary
        .color
          .sample(class='brown')
          .name Brown
          .hex #961e1d
        .color
          .sample(class='green')
          .name Green
          .hex #129612
        .color
          .sample(class='grape')
          .name Grape
          .hex #b400b4

  .guide
    .content
      h2 Production
      p Connecticut statute specifies the dimensions of the flag in feet and inches. It should have a fly of 5 feet, 6 inches and a hoist of 4 feet, 4 inches.
      p If resized, it must maintain these proportions.
      p The flag should be made of silk.
    .visual
      img(src='/assets/images/flag-connecticut-dimensions.svg')

